    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>NATURAL GAS PRICES COULD HURT MEXICO</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Graham Gori</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Gori, Graham</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Canacintra, leading Mexican industrial group, warns that at least 500 Mexican glass, steel and ceramics plants might be forced to lay off 250,000 workers this winter because of rising natural gas prices; Canacintra blames state-run oil monopoly, Pemex, for raising natural gas prices in absence of competition; Pemex, which is expected to earn windfall from Mexican oil and gas production this year, says increased demand has forced it to raise prices (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>A leading Mexican industrial group warned yesterday that at least 500 Mexican glass, steel and ceramic plants might be forced to lay off 250,000 workers this winter because of rising natural gas prices. The trade group, known as Canacintra, blamed the state-run oil monopoly, Pemex, for raising natural gas prices in the absence of competition. Pemex, which is expected to earn a windfall from Mexican oil and gas production this year, said increased demand had forced it to raise prices.</p>
        <p>Graham Gori</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
